<subSubSection id="A12A18513F6CAD97B28451FF4BE9EEA7" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" type="notes">
<paragraph id="8DA3DA056688C8B659F960DFBABB9DD8" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F6C59969CD4A25B4B7AC33F34383E627" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
<taxonomicName id="C081F4977157B9D16EFB99FF1CAA8B77" authorityName="W. H. Chen &amp; Y. M. Shui" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Oreocharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oreocharis wenshanensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wenshanensis">
<emphasis id="32B516947FE02AED02F0B1F1C370AF22" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Oreocharis wenshanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected first in 1993 by Y. M. Shui in Wenshan county, SE Yunnan, China (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F53D888B8D54378104119CF88409A218" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Oreocharis eriocarpa W. H. Chen &amp; Y. M. Shui, sp. nov. (A-F) A habit B leaf adaxial surface C leaf abaxial surface D bracts E ovary and disc F dense pubescent ovary and disc; O. wenshanensis (G-K) G habitat H plant I leaf adaxial surface J leaf abaxial surface K flower. Photography by He De-Ming (A-E, K), Zhang Ting (E), Chen Li (F), Shui Yu-Min (G, I, J)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys..32284.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/445709" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">2G-K</figureCitation>
). In 2005, the new species was wrongly identified as 
<taxonomicName id="6143523E03907F7E891B6A55FF1FF970" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Oreocharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oreocharis aurea subsp. var. var. cordato-ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="aurea" subSpecies="var." variety="cordato-ovata">Oreocharis aurea Dunn var. cordato-ovata</taxonomicName>
(C.Y. Wu ex H.W. Li) K.Y. Pan, A.L. Weitzman &amp; L.E. Skog, based on the photo in 
<bibRefCitation id="A12566EC4B585F49E21122845368D6B5" author="Li, ZY" journalOrPublisher="Vol. 5. Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" refId="B9" refString="Li, ZY, Wang, YZ, 2005. Plants of Gesneriaceae in China. Henan Science Technology Publishing House, Zhengzhou, 14-47." title="Plants of Gesneriaceae in China. Henan Science Technology Publishing House, Zhengzhou, 14 - 47." year="2005">Li and Wang (2005)</bibRefCitation>
possibly because of their similar locality in SE Yunnan. However, the latter species endemically grows in the limestone forests in Xichou county, the neighbouring county of Wenshan county, a very different habitat from 
<taxonomicName id="608B88CB7A3507991DF71213D137FAF8" authorityName="W. H. Chen &amp; Y. M. Shui" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Oreocharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oreocharis wenshanensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wenshanensis">
<emphasis id="01CC71BF6E1A7094FE7E16B94CFB6D07" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Oreocharis wenshanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Furthermore, the new species we proposed can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="A7AB0274804BEBFD0F06FA38C010BFE9" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Oreocharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oreocharis aurea subsp. var. var. cordato-ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="aurea" subSpecies="var." variety="cordato-ovata">Oreocharis aurea Dunn var. cordato-ovata</taxonomicName>
by its broadly ovate blade, smaller corolla without contracted throat and bilobed adaxial corolla lips (
<bibRefCitation id="96B83C5E1D937841CB238B10360ACA5A" author="Li, ZY" journalOrPublisher="Vol. 5. Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" refId="B9" refString="Li, ZY, Wang, YZ, 2005. Plants of Gesneriaceae in China. Henan Science Technology Publishing House, Zhengzhou, 14-47." title="Plants of Gesneriaceae in China. Henan Science Technology Publishing House, Zhengzhou, 14 - 47." year="2005">Li and Wang 2005</bibRefCitation>
). In fact, due to its 2700 m elevation, it is morphologically more similar to 
<taxonomicName id="687B322B75401101081643B19C8D8B48" genus="O." lsidName="O. concava" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="concava">
<emphasis id="7EF71322204AFB74E732D04E9C2CF0D7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">O. concava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from NW Yunnan with 3100-3400 m elevation (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E7F12511B9931AD52AD4318C32CD243A" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Oreocharis wenshanensis W. H. Chen &amp; Y. M. Shui, sp. nov. A plant B opened corolla showing stamens and staminode C pistil showing ovary, disc and stigma D calyx. (Drawn by Ling Wang from holotype)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys..32284.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/445714" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">7</figureCitation>
, Table 
<tableCitation id="852A8736AC37E57805DEA090D11D3D79" captionStart="Table 4" captionStartId="T4" captionText="Table 4. Differences between Oreocharis wenshanensis and O. concava in Gesneriaceae." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/6EF94C2A88B7B2D09EBB5E0DFC3D4E68" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" tableUuid="6EF94C2A88B7B2D09EBB5E0DFC3D4E68">4</tableCitation>
). After more than 20 years of observation, with the support of local staff of the Nature Reserve, we made a long-term observation from 1993 to 2018 and confirmed its taxonomic novelty.
</paragraph>
<caption id="6EF94C2A88B7B2D09EBB5E0DFC3D4E68" ID-Table-UUID="6EF94C2A88B7B2D09EBB5E0DFC3D4E68" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/6EF94C2A88B7B2D09EBB5E0DFC3D4E68" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" start="Table 4" startId="T4">
